      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Mideast Hope</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Theodore Corin letter disputes Thomas L Friedman's October 17 Op-Ed column on violence in Middle East</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>If, as Thomas L. Friedman writes (''The Wrong Answer,'' column, Oct. 17), the devil and the solution in the Middle East crisis are in the details, the quintessential detail is surely a lack of ''mutually assured humanity.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>If, as Thomas L. Friedman writes (''The Wrong Answer,'' column, Oct. 17), the devil and the solution in the Middle East crisis are in the details, the quintessential detail is surely a lack of ''mutually assured humanity.''</p>
        <p>Once the bloodletting has ceased, the next step in the triage should be to persuade the Palestinian and Israeli leaders to proclaim jointly that each regards the lives and human rights of the other to be equally and mutually valuable.</p>
        <p>Words to this effect could provide a powerful and much-needed symbolic basis for a fresh start of the peace process.</p>
        <p>THEODORE CORIN  Austin, Tex., Oct. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
